GitNotes

#Ways to use Git
   •/Local_Version_Control
      ◦Saves files to database on computer
   •/Centralized_Version_Control
      ◦Saves files to a database on a network server
   •/Distributed_Version_Control
      ◦Saves files to a database on a interweb server

#File States in Git
   •/Modified
      ◦Files that have been changed
   •/Staged
      ◦Files to be saved
   •/Committed_Files
      ◦Files that have been saved

#Configeration of Git Bash
   •/Username
      ◦‘git config --global user.name [name]’ 
   •/Email
      ◦‘git config --global user.email [email] ’
   •/Core
      ◦‘git core.editor vim’

#Directory Navigation
   •/Commands
      ◦‘cd’    (Change Directory)
      ◦‘ls’    (Show contents of directory)
      ◦‘ls -a’ (Show content + hidden files of dirrectory)
      ◦‘mkdir’ (Create new folder)

#Initializing a Repository
   •/Init_master
      ◦‘git init’
      ◦‘git add .’
      ◦ ‘git commit -m “Comment”’
   •/Ignoring_Files (from tracking in directory)
      ◦Create .gitignore file
         ▸ ‘touch .gitignore’
         ▸[.filetype] to ignore filetypes
         ▸[foldername/] to ignore folders

#Managing Files
   •/Comitting_Staged
      ◦‘git commit -m "Message’
   •/Staging
      ◦‘git add [filename.filetype][*][*.filetype]’
         ▸‘*’ translates to ALL
   •/Getting_changes
      ◦‘git diff’
   •/Skipping_Staging
      ◦‘git commit -a’
   •/Deleting
      ◦ ‘git rm [filename.filetype]’
         ▸if staged, force delete: ‘git rm -f [filename.filetype]’
   •/Remove_from_staging
      ◦‘git rm --cached [filename.filetype]’
   •/Renaming
      ◦‘git mv [filename.filetype] [newfilename.filetype]’


   “Look up log commands to document”
#Logs
   •/Log_messages (in reverse chronological order)
      ◦‘git log’
   •/Logs_formatted
      ◦‘git log --pretty=oneline’
   •Log messages formatted
      ◦‘git log --pretty=format:[format codes]’
         ▸‘%h’(Hash code abbreviation)
         ▸‘%an’(Name of User that made change)
         ▸‘%ar’(What time change was made relative to current time)
         ▸ ‘%s’(First line in commit message.)
